Kaduna State Government on Wednesday swore in a commissioner and two permanent secretaries,  charging them to be committed and trustworthy. Hajiya Umma Aboki was sworn in as the state Commissioner for Planning and Budget, while Messrs Kabir Mainasibi and Bashir Muhammad were sworn-in as Permanent Secretaries. In her remarks at the ceremony, the state Deputy Gov.  Hadiza Balarabe charged the officials to avoid distractions and discharge duties well. According to the deputy governor, responsibility comes with trust. She urged the officials to show a high level of commitment and justify the confidence reposed in them. 		 			Strike: ASUU tackles Fed Govt over N4trn fuel subsidy budget		 		 		 			Abductors demand N100m ransom for popular Akwa Ibom cleric		 		 		 			Many killed, houses burnt as Ilaje, Ibeno clash in Akwa Ibom		 		 According to her, the appointments are in recognition of hard work and competence. “I, therefore, hope that you will uphold and protect this confidence that has been reposed in you, “she said. She thanked the state Gov. Nasir El- Rufai for recognising competence. “Our governor recognises performance and rewards it,” she said. She noted that the appointment brought to eight, the number of female commissioners in the state and 17,  the total number of commissioners in Kaduna State. NAN reports that Aboki, until her appointment, was a Permanent Secretary in the state Ministry of Planning and Budget. Aboki replaced  Muhammad Sani Dattijo who recently resigned to join  2023 Kaduna State governorship race  (NAN)